Equation 5: Allocate breeding females to sink habitat (B.fk)

eq05calcScalar.Rd

This function allocates breeding (B.) females (f) to to sink habitat (k).

eq05calcScalar(K.bc, K.bk, W2)

Arguments

K.bc

sour.c.e K
K.bk

sin.k. K
W2

population vector

Value

K.bk, the ... xxxx

Details

This function compares total number of females (W2"fg" + W2"fp") against K.bc, the carrying capacity ("K.") of the breeding-ground (".b.") source habiat (".c")

Notes: 1)If W2"fg" + W2"fp" < K.bc, then ALL birds went to the sour.c.e (via the previous function) and 0 birds end up going to the breeding sink

2)If K.bc < W2"fg" + W2"fp", then the total female pop is larger the source carrying capacity and all birds cannot go to source. (That is, the nubmer of females is in excess of the amount of source habitat) Therefore, some birds will go to source and some to sink, with birds wintering in high quality habitat having preference

So, if K.bc < (W2"fg" + W2"fp") AND W2"fg" + W2"fp" < (K.bc+K.bk) (tot fem pop less than combined source and sink k) then number that go to the sink is W2"fg" + W2"fp" - K.bc That is, the number going to the sink is anything left after allocation to the source K.bc

3)If W2"fg" + W2"fp" >= (K.bc+K.bk) (tot fem pop >= combined K of both habitats) then both the source and the sink get completely filled up and any remaining female birds, from the perspective of the model die (!)

This is explained by the authors: "dd is implicit in EQUATION (5): females displaced from sink habitat are presumed to die. This is a 'ceiling' form of dd - no effect is evident until the number of arriving females exceeds the combined carrying capacity of the source and sink habitats" (Runge and Marra 2004, pg 378)

Aliased as F.2.sink.eq5.k()

References

Runge, MC and PP Marra. 2004. Modeling seasonal interactions in the population dynamics of migratory birds. In Greenberg, R and PP Marra, eds. Birds of two worlds. Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore.
